data.title: Jäätteenmäki will not run for president
data.meta_description: Former Centre party Prime Minister and current MEP Anneli Jäätteenmäki will not be a candidate in next year’s presidential election. Meanwhile another party veteran, Mauri Pekkarinen, is to announce whether he will run on Tuesday, and the Swedish People’s Party will name its candidate.
data.text:
Jäätteenmäki cited her lack of enthusiasm for the presidency, and said that she did not want to run for office just out of a sense of duty. She told YLE of her decision in Brussels. She said she had mulled over a presidential run for a long while, and it was time to announce her decision after her summer holiday.

The former Prime Minister had originally informed current Centre Party chair Mari Kiviniemi of her decision on 3 August. She considered changing her mind, but in the end decided it was the right choice.

Kiviniemi, who served as Prime Minister herself in the last government, said that Jäätteenmäki’s decision was regrettable, but confirmed that she will not run for president either.

Leading Centre party figures Olli Rehn, Matti Vanhanen and Seppo Kääriäinen had already ruled themselves out of the running. That could leave the field clear for Paavo Väyrynen, the veteran Centre politician who lost his parliamentary seat at the last election and has repeatedly declared his desire to win the party’s nomination. However he seems to have little support among the party faithful.

Long-time government minister Mauri Pekkarinen is to announce his decision on Tuesday, reports the daily Savon Sanomat.

The Centre’s deadline for announcing candidacies is 9 September.

Swedish Party to name candidate

Meanwhile the small Swedish People’s Party is to name its presidential candidate on this afternoon. The nod is expected to go to Eva Biaudet, now Ombudsman for Ethnic Minorities. She is a former minister of health and social services, United Nations official and the OSCE Special Representative for Combating Trafficking in Human Beings.

The party’s secretary has suggested that the Centre Party might support the SPP’s candidate.
